      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_ Princeton_1834-06_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="New-Burlington-Street_ENK"/>
                  <date when="1834-06-30"/>June 30, 1834.</dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>Madam,</persName><!--Still a bit confused about the salute tags. Do I include the salute here as well as below?-->
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Copy of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentR1">Bentley's</persName><lb/>
               Madam,<lb/>
               As I shall shortly approach the sale of the number of<lb/>
               copies which would authorize me to transmit to you<lb/>
               a further promissory note for the contingent <add>£</add>200<lb/>
               contemplated in the agreement for the first Ed<hi rend="superscript">n</hi><lb/>
               of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Helen1">"Helen"</title> I beg to say that I am ready to transmit<lb/>
               such promissory note by post to you if you please<lb/>
               or to hand the same to any agent in London whom<lb/>
               you may authorize to receive it -<lb/></p>
               <p>As I trust you will consider that the publication<lb/>
               of this work has in my hands been followed<lb/>
               up with zeal and activity and that your own<lb/>
               wishes have been punctually fulfilled may I<lb/>
               take occasion to say that I shall be most <hi rend="underline">happy</hi><lb/>
               to be entrusted by you with the publication of<lb/>
               the story called <hi rend="underline">"Granting for <unclear>Granted</unclear>"</hi> to which<lb/>
               M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ1">Lockhart</persName> alluded when I had the pleasure<lb/>
               negotiating with him for <title ref="./Workography.xml#Helen1">Helen</title> - And to<lb/>
               solicit the favor of your acquainting me at what<lb/>
               time you intend to give your next novel to<lb/>
               the world. I have the honor to be<lb/>
               Madam with great respect<lb/>
               your most good &amp; humble Ser<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentR1">Richard Bentley</persName><lb/></p>
               <p>Answer<lb/><!--Second letter within this letter begins here and is on the same page-->
               July 1834<lb/>
               Sir<lb/>
               I am glad to hear that you approach the sale of<lb/>
               the number of copies<add>of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Helen1">Helen</title></add> which enables you to transmit<lb/>
               to me the <del>further</del> promissory <add>note</add> you mention for<lb/>
               £200 - Whenever you are ready I beg you will<lb/>
               give the note to my brother in law <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">L. P. Wilson Esq</persName><hi rend="superscript">r</hi><lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#1-North-Audley-Street_ENK">N<hi rend="superscript">o</hi> 1 North Audley Street</placeName> or to my sister<lb/> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>.<lb/>
               Wilson</persName> whichever of them happen to be at home<lb/>
               - <del>they</del> <add>Either of them</add> will give you a receipt for me -<lb/></p>
               <p>I have every reason to be satisfied with<lb/>
               the manner in which you have brought out this<lb/>
               book, and <del>to be</del> <add>am</add> obliged by the <del>and</del> <add>promptness</add> and <del></del> <add>care</add> <del>punc</del><lb/>
               <del>quality</del> with which you have complied with my<lb/>
               wishes as to presentation copies and on all other<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <!--Where there's a page break record it inside the relevant body paragraph like this, 
                  with the self-closing page-break element. n="2" indicates the START of the second page.-->
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_ Princeton_1834-06_page02.jpg"/>
            </p>
            <p>points as well as with your punctuality in<lb/>
               fulfilling your agreement as to money matters<lb/></p>
               <p>I will let you know whenever I <del>think</del><lb/>
               <del>of</del> I am again ready to go to press or to <del>make</del> <add>enter into</add><lb/>
               any agreement for another work - But<lb/>
               I make it a rule never to <del>make</del> <add>enter into</add> any agree<lb/>
               ment or <add>give</add> any promise for a<del>ny</del> manuscript<lb/>
               till it is absolutely finished - <del>And</del> I have<lb/>
               none at present even approaching to that<lb/>
               condition - Nor can I tell when I may be<lb/>
               ready to publish again -<lb/>
               I am Sir<lb/>
               Your Obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> &amp; humble<lb/>
               Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi><lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/></p>
